      <guid>http://localhost:52794/docs/Mathematics/MATH-412-Real-Analysis-II/%E7%AC%AC%E4%B8%83%E7%AB%A0/7.1.1-Inverse-FT-Proof/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;71-implicit-function-theorem-ift-proof&#34;&gt;&#xA;  7.1* Implicit Function Theorem (IFT) Proof&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#71-implicit-function-theorem-ift-proof&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;1-recall-ift&#34;&gt;&#xA;  1. Recall IFT&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#1-recall-ift&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theorem 7.1.1:&lt;/strong&gt; Let $y = f(x): A \subset \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^n$ be of class $C^1$. Suppose $x_0 \in A$ with:&#xA;$$&#xA;J_f(x_0) = \det(Df(x_0)) \ne 0&#xA;$$&#xA;Then there exist neighborhoods $U$ of $x_0$ in $A$ and $W$ of $y_0 = f(x_0)$ such that:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;$f(U) = W$ and $f: U \to W$ has an inverse $f^{-1}: W \to U$.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;$f^{-1} \in C^1$ (If $f \in C^r$, then $f^{-1} \in C^r$).&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;$Df^{-1}(y) = [Df(x)]^{-1}$ for $x \in U$ and $y = f(x)$.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;2-proof-of-theorem-711&#34;&gt;&#xA;  2. Proof of Theorem 7.1.1&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#2-proof-of-theorem-711&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;step-1-reduction&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Step 1: Reduction&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#step-1-reduction&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;We may assume $Df(x_0) = I$ and $x_0 = 0$, $y_0 = f(x_0)$.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
